   <text xml:lang="en" type="original">
      <front>
         <dhq:abstract>
            <p>The increasing prevalence of computer models within humanities research has raised a number of challenges for humanities scholars. Chief 
               among them are the ways in which computational modelling fundamentally transforms the conventional methodologies and epistemological 
               frameworks that have long defined research within the humanities. In <title rend="italic">Modelling Between Digital and Humanities: 
               Thinking in Practice</title> (2023), <name>Arianna Ciula</name>, <name>Ã˜yvind Eide</name>, <name>Cristina Marras</name>, and 
               <name>Patrick Sahle</name> evaluate the impact of this paradigm shift on humanities scholarship and varying strategies for addressing 
               the challenges that it presents. In particular, the authors take up the idea of formulating a new digital humanities mode of thinking 
               that can enable the humanities to adapt and thrive in the digital age while retaining their core values.
            </p>
         </dhq:abstract>
